+        <tr><td>inverse</td><td><code>(a+bε)⁻¹ = 1/a − b/a² ε</code></td><td>exists exactly when <code>a≠0</code></td></tr>
+        <tr><td>division</td><td><code>(a+bε)/(c+dε)=a/c + (bc-ad)/c² ε</code></td><td>requires <code>c≠0</code></td></tr>
+      </tbody>
+    </table></div>
+  </section>
+
+  <section class="dual-columns">
+    <article>
+      <h2>algebraic facts</h2>
+      <ul>
+        <li><strong>Not a field:</strong> every nonzero pure infinitesimal <code>bε</code> has no inverse.</li>
+        <li><strong>Zero divisors:</strong> <code>ε · ε = 0</code> although <code>ε ≠ 0</code>.</li>
+        <li><strong>Units:</strong> <code>a+bε</code> is invertible iff its real part <code>a</code> is nonzero.</li>
+        <li><strong>Local ring:</strong> the non-units form the maximal ideal <code>(ε)</code>; the residue field is <code>R</code>.</li>
+        <li><strong>Nilpotents:</strong> all elements of <code>(ε)</code> square to zero.</li>
+        <li><strong>Conjugation:</strong> sometimes <code>¯(a+bε)=a-bε</code>, but <code>(a+bε)(a-bε)=a²</code>, not a norm that detects ε.</li>
+      </ul>
+    </article>
+    <article>
+      <h2>functions</h2>
+      <p>If <code>f</code> is differentiable at <code>a</code>, the nilpotence of ε truncates the Taylor series after the linear term:</p>
+      <p class="dual-formula"><code>f(a+bε) = f(a) + b f′(a) ε</code></p>
